{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YXyBf33qckdE7NChKjBUhG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see:\n- 3-node RabbitMQ cluster running 3.9-management\n- /app vhost exists with app-queue having 5 messages\n- PVCs are bound for all 3 nodes\n\nNow I need to plan the upgrade from 3.9 to 4.1. \n\n**Important considerations for RabbitMQ upgrades:**\n\nRabbitMQ 3.9 → 4.1 is a **major version skip** (skipping 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, 4.0). RabbitMQ's upgrade policy says you should upgrade one minor version at a time for major versions - specifically:\n- 3.9 → 3.10 → 3.11 → 3.12 → 3.13 → 4.0 → 4.1\n\nBut the namespace is labeled \"manual_skip_upgrade,\" which suggests we're attempting to skip intermediate versions. Looking at the RabbitMQ documentation more carefully, while the recommended path is incremental, skip upgrades from 3.9 directly to 4.1 are technically possible but require careful handling of the cluster state and configuration changes between versions.\n\nThe critical issue is that RabbitMQ 4.0 introduced major architectural changes—Mnesia was replaced with Khepri as the metadata store, and the on-disk format changed significantly. For a direct 3.9 → 4.1 upgrade, I need to determine whether the migration path preserves data or requires a fresh cluster setup.\n\nThe task name \"manual_skip_upgrade\" suggests we're testing whether it's possible to skip the intermediate 3.13.x step (the last 3.x version that bridges both storage formats) and jump directly to 4.1. According to RabbitMQ's official guidance, this shouldn't be possible without data loss, but the test case name implies this is exactly what we're being asked to attempt. set compatibility between 3.9 and 4.1 is uncertain, so I need to consider whether a rolling upgrade will actually work or if intermediate versions are necessary. The practical approach would be attempting the direct upgrade through a rolling update where each pod gets updated sequentially, but I'm realizing there's a critical constraint: all nodes in a cluster must run the same version during upgrades, which means I can't have 3.9 and 4.1 nodes coexisting. to complete. Feature flags will be enabled after the 3.13 cluster stabilizes, then I'll proceed with the final upgrade to 4.1 using the same rolling update strategy.\n\nNow I need to check what configuration is currently being used for the RabbitMQ settings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":490,"cache_read_input_tokens":32090,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":490},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"74643e4c-336b-4456-86ab-ce7c25c206bf","uuid":"6642facf-1003-4f56-96bf-09fa4bd0635a","request_id":"req_011CcMtRa1Wi6PHFhkq5NicF"}
