{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01G2KY5ayvX74q6hGzoab9ee","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The kind cluster has these images available:\n- rabbitmq:3.9-management (current)\n- rabbitmq:3.10-management\n- rabbitmq:3.11-management\n- rabbitmq:3.12-management\n- rabbitmq:3.13-management\n- rabbitmq:4.1-management\n\nSo the upgrade path will be:\n1. 3.9 → 3.12 (skip 3.10 and 3.11 since we have 3.12 available, but need to check if this works)\n\nWait, actually the issue is which feature flags are required by each version. Let me think again:\n- 3.10 introduces `classic_mirrored_queue_version`\n- 3.12 may introduce other required flags\n- 3.13 requires `classic_mirrored_queue_version` to be enabled\n\nThe question is whether I can jump directly from 3.9 to 3.12, skipping the intermediate versions. This depends on whether 3.12 requires any feature flags from 3.10 to be pre-enabled, or if it can handle the upgrade without those prerequisites. 3.12 likely introduces its own flags that become mandatory in 3.13, so I need to understand RabbitMQ's feature flag requirements more carefully.\n\nLooking at what flags were introduced in each version: 3.10 added `classic_mirrored_queue_version`, `stream_single_active_consumer`, and `feature_flags_v2`, while 3.11 added several others like `at_most_once_dead_lettering`, `direct_exchange_routing_v2`, and `listener_records_in_ets`.\n\nBy 3.13, all of these earlier flags become required—meaning the code no longer supports running without them enabled, so any upgrade from an older version needs to have them activated first. The key question is whether 3.11 requires flags from 3.10 to be enabled at startup—if `feature_flags_v2` fundamentally changes how flag management works, then 3.11 might fail to start with 3.9 data that doesn't have it enabled. I should test the upgrade path empirically by trying 3.9 → 3.11 directly first. All the 3.9 feature flags are already enabled, so the real question is whether I can jump directly to 3.12 or if I need intermediate steps like 3.10 and 3.11 to handle the data migration properly.\n\nThe concern is that 3.12 might require certain flags that were introduced in 3.10 or 3.11 (like `classic_mirrored_queue_version` or `feature_flags_v2`) to be present and enabled before it will start, and since 3.9 never had those flags, the upgrade could fail. I need to check whether 3.12 actually marks those intermediate flags as required at startup or if it can recognize and auto-enable them. and flags from 3.11 and 3.12, so you'd need to enable those intermediate flags before upgrading to 3.13. This means 3.9 → 3.10 → 3.11 → 3.12 → 3.13 is the safest path if you're starting from 3.9. ones from 3.12). But wait, can we actually skip 3.10 and 3.11 entirely? That depends on whether 3.12 requires flags that were introduced in those versions. Let me think through the pragmatic approach: I have images for 3.9, 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 4.1, so I should test whether jumping directly from 3.9 to 3.12 is viable. → Then we need 3.10 as an intermediate step. Looking at the RabbitMQ 3.12 release notes, it requires `feature_flags_v2` to be enabled before upgrading, and since that flag was introduced in 3.10, we can't skip it from 3.9. The question now is whether we can jump directly from 3.10 to 3.12, skipping 3.11 entirely.\n\nRather than speculate about which flags 3.12 might require from 3.11, I should test this empirically using a single pod with partition=2 to see if a direct 3.9 → 3.12 upgrade fails with a missing flag error, then work backward through intermediate versions if needed. I'm going to stick with the safer incremental path: 3.9 → 3.10 → 3.11 → 3.12 → 3.13 → 4.1, since all those images are available and upgrading one minor version at a time is the most reliable approach. For each step, I'll set the partition to 2 so rabbitmq-2 gets updated first, then update the StatefulSet image.\n\nThe key workflow is: update the pod, wait for it to rejoin the cluster, enable all feature flags cluster-wide, then move to the next pod. The StatefulSet controller will handle the pod lifecycle automatically. 6. Wait for rabbitmq-1 to rejoin, then patch again to update rabbitmq-0 as well\n7. Once rabbitmq-0 is ready, verify the entire cluster is healthy and running version Y\n\nFor the 3.9 to 3.10 upgrade specifically, I'm checking whether feature flags can be enabled while the cluster is in a mixed version state—3.10 should handle 3.9 data without requiring any pre-existing flags, so enabling them after the first node updates should work.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the safer approach is to upgrade all nodes to the new version first, then enable feature flags afterward, rather than trying to enable them mid-upgrade. So I should set the image to 3.10 with partition 0 to update everything at once, wait for all pods to stabilize on 3.10, then enable the feature flags. Then repeat this pattern for each subsequent version jump through 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 4.1. I need to figure out which version jumps I can skip rather than going through every intermediate step. Let me check what config changes are required for 4.x—specifically that `queue_master_locator` setting was removed, and I should verify the `rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s` plugin still works in 4.1 along with the guest user configuration.\n\nThe key question is whether I can jump from 3.9 directly to 3.12 or if I need to step through each version. Some feature flags introduced in 3.10 might be required by 3.11, which would force me to go through the intermediate step. I'll test this empirically by trying the most aggressive skip first—updating to 3.12 on a single partition to see if it starts cleanly with 3.9 data.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2231,"cache_read_input_tokens":48916,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tok